If you need to access the global object without hard-coding the identifier window, you can do the following from any level of nested function scope: var global = (function () {
    return this;
}());

That’s why a better pattern for for loops is to cache the length of the array (or collection) you’re iterating over, as shown in the following example: for (var i = 0, max = myarray.length; i < max; i++) {
    // do something with myarray[i]
}

Here is the general-purpose currying function: function schonfinkelize(fn) {
    var slice = Array.prototype.slice,
        stored_args = slice.call(arguments, 1);
    return function () {
        var new_args = slice.call(arguments),
            args = stored_args.concat(new_args);
        return fn.apply(null, args);
    };
}
